<subSubSection id="C3108DCECA6D5A62F0BDFB39FD876FEF" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB5DE45CA6D5A62F0BDFB39FB386C6C" blockId="12.[151,1437,1187,1871]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="B97E0257CA6D5A62F0BDFB39FEB36C3E" bold="true" box="[198,351,1264,1290]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Description.</emphasis>
The depicted colony (
<figureCitation id="1331C2C0CA6D5A62F211FB38FD5D6C3F" box="[618,689,1265,1291]" captionStart="FIGURE 7. a" captionStartId="13.[151,255,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[175,1418,197,1952]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[175,1419,197,1953]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 7. a, RMNH Coel. 38768, holotype of Astrogorgia fruticosa n. sp.; b, RMNH Coel. 38769, Echinogorgia sp. a; c, RMNH Coel. 38770, Echinogorgia sp. b; d, RMNH Coel. 38771, Echinogorgia sp. b. Scales 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/186750/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Fig. 
<number id="3DC2CC62CA6D5A62F2D9FB38FD5D6C3F" box="[674,689,1265,1291]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
c) is 
<quantity id="4CF273A0CA6D5A62F290FB38FCCB6C3F" box="[747,807,1265,1291]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="cm" value="8.0">8 cm</quantity>
high and 
<quantity id="4CF273A0CA6D5A62F3E5FB38FC046C3F" box="[926,1000,1265,1291]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="cm" value="10.0">10 cm</quantity>
wide, growing on a piece of rock. It branches loosely, more or less in one plane; branches are very slender, about 
<quantity id="4CF273A0CA6D5A62F453FAD1FB806C06" box="[1064,1132,1304,1330]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
wide. Polyps are situated all around the branches, the calyces are very low, hardly protruding above the coenenchyme.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB5DE45CA6D5A62F0BEFAACFCE26C92" blockId="12.[151,1437,1187,1871]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Polyps are retracted, having few, almost smooth sclerites, up to 
<quantity id="4CF273A0CA6D5A62F3D7FAACFBF86C4B" box="[940,1044,1381,1407]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="0.15">0.15 mm</quantity>
long (
<figureCitation id="1331C2C0CA6D5A62F425FAACFB5D6C4B" box="[1118,1201,1381,1407]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="17.[151,260,1974,1998]" captionTargetBox="[172,1415,194,1950]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[172,1416,194,1950]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 11. RMNH Coel. 38770, Echinogorgia sp. b: a, polyp spindles; b, spindles of the subsurface layer; c, thornscales of surface layer; d, capstan derivatives of the subsurface layer." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/186754/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Fig. 
<number id="3DC2CC62CA6D5A62F4EFFAACFB5D6C4B" box="[1172,1201,1381,1407]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
a). We could not see a clear difference between collaret and point sclerites.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB5DE45CA6D5A62F0BEFA7BFD616F74" blockId="12.[151,1437,1187,1871]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Surface layer of the coenenchyme has thornscales, most up to 
<quantity id="4CF273A0CA6D5A62F3ACFA7BFBA96CF8" box="[983,1093,1458,1484]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="0.25">0.25 mm</quantity>
long, a few 
<quantity id="4CF273A0CA6D5A62F49EFA7BFABF6CF8" box="[1253,1363,1458,1484]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="0.4">0.40 mm</quantity>
long; additionally a few unilaterally spinose spindles are present (
<figureCitation id="1331C2C0CA6D5A62F322FA10FC556CC7" box="[857,953,1497,1523]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="17.[151,260,1974,1998]" captionTargetBox="[172,1415,194,1950]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[172,1416,194,1950]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 11. RMNH Coel. 38770, Echinogorgia sp. b: a, polyp spindles; b, spindles of the subsurface layer; c, thornscales of surface layer; d, capstan derivatives of the subsurface layer." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/186754/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Figs. 
<number id="3DC2CC62CA6D5A62F3E7FA10FC556CC7" box="[924,953,1497,1523]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
c, 
<number id="3DC2CC62CA6D5A62F3AFFA10FC1F6CC7" box="[980,1011,1497,1523]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="12.0">12</number>
a). The inner layer with spindles, up to 
<quantity id="4CF273A0CA6D5A62F0CCF9C9FEC86F2E" box="[183,292,1536,1562]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="0.45">0.45 mm</quantity>
long, many heavily branched (
<figureCitation id="1331C2C0CA6D5A62F2DAF9C9FD116F2E" box="[673,765,1536,1562]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="17.[151,260,1974,1998]" captionTargetBox="[172,1415,194,1950]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[172,1416,194,1950]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 11. RMNH Coel. 38770, Echinogorgia sp. b: a, polyp spindles; b, spindles of the subsurface layer; c, thornscales of surface layer; d, capstan derivatives of the subsurface layer." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/186754/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Figs 
<number id="3DC2CC62CA6D5A62F29BF9C9FD116F2E" box="[736,765,1536,1562]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
b, 
<number id="3DC2CC62CA6D5A62F367F9C9FCD06F2E" box="[796,828,1536,1562]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="12.0">12</number>
b). Furthermore, small derivatives of capstans are present, most up to 
<quantity id="4CF273A0CA6D5A62F106F9EFFE236F74" box="[381,463,1574,1600]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="m" value="0.05">0.05 m</quantity>
long (
<figureCitation id="1331C2C0CA6D5A62F261F9EFFD826F74" box="[538,622,1574,1600]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="17.[151,260,1974,1998]" captionTargetBox="[172,1415,194,1950]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[172,1416,194,1950]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 11. RMNH Coel. 38770, Echinogorgia sp. b: a, polyp spindles; b, spindles of the subsurface layer; c, thornscales of surface layer; d, capstan derivatives of the subsurface layer." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/186754/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Fig. 
<number id="3DC2CC62CA6D5A62F22AF9EFFD826F74" box="[593,622,1574,1600]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
d).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB5DE45CA6D5A62F0BEF984FD7F6F53" blockId="12.[151,1437,1187,1871]" box="[197,659,1613,1639]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="B97E0257CA6D5A62F0BEF984FECD6F53" bold="true" box="[197,289,1613,1639]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Colour.</emphasis>
Colony ochre, sclerites yellow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB5DE45CA6D5A62F0BEF9BAFD876FEF" blockId="12.[151,1437,1187,1871]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="B97E0257CA6D5A62F0BEF9BAFEBD6FB9" bold="true" box="[197,337,1651,1677]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Variability.</emphasis>
The other three colonies from Farur Island are similar to the one here described. The colonies from 
<collectingCountry id="F31D9ED5CA6D5A62F0A7F952FEDF6F81" box="[220,307,1691,1717]" name="Iran" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Qeshm</collectingCountry>
Island (
<figureCitation id="1331C2C0CA6D5A62F1E2F952FE0F6F81" box="[409,483,1691,1717]" captionStart="FIGURE 7. a" captionStartId="13.[151,255,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[175,1418,197,1952]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[175,1419,197,1953]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 7. a, RMNH Coel. 38768, holotype of Astrogorgia fruticosa n. sp.; b, RMNH Coel. 38769, Echinogorgia sp. a; c, RMNH Coel. 38770, Echinogorgia sp. b; d, RMNH Coel. 38771, Echinogorgia sp. b. Scales 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/186750/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Fig. 
<number id="3DC2CC62CA6D5A62F1AFF952FE0F6F81" box="[468,483,1691,1717]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
d) are yellow, more loosely branched with slightly wider branches, but have sclerites similar to 
<collectionCode id="ED1B4680CA6D5A62F10EF908FE216FEF" LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34992" box="[373,461,1729,1755]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34992" name="National Museum of Natural History, Naturalis" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">RMNH</collectionCode>
Coel. 
<number id="3DC2CC62CA6D5A62F261F908FD8B6FEF" box="[538,615,1729,1755]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="38770.0">38770</number>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3108DCECA6D5A62F0BEF92EFE246E7B" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BB5DE45CA6D5A62F0BEF92EFE246E7B" blockId="12.[151,1437,1187,1871]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="B97E0257CA6D5A62F0BEF92EFEAD6E35" bold="true" box="[197,321,1767,1793]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species differs from species-a above in lacking anastomoses, being yellow to ochre in colour, and in having smaller polyp spindles and interior capstan derivatives, and in having interior spindles which are more branched.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
